9:["$","section",null,{"className":"mb-12","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Rate Mechanics"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"Bitget uses traditional order book-based funding with 8-hour intervals tied to mark price deviations from spot. GMX employs hourly funding settlements based on oracle prices and utilization of its GLP liquidity pools. The higher frequency on GMX reduces funding rate volatility but may increase gas costs for arbitrageurs. Bitget's CEX model offers more predictable funding patterns but relies on centralized price discovery."}]]}]
a:["$","$Le",null,{"items":[{"question":"Which exchange has better funding rate opportunities?","answer":"Bitget's 8-hour intervals create larger rate swings, potentially offering better arbitrage opportunities. GMX's hourly settlements provide more frequent but smaller rate changes, requiring different strategies."},{"question":"How do the fee structures compare for funding arbitrage?","answer":"Bitget offers significantly lower trading fees (0.02%/0.06% vs 0.05%/0.07%) which is crucial for arbitrage profitability. However, GMX's decentralized nature eliminates counterparty risk and withdrawal delays."},{"question":"Which platform is more reliable for automated strategies?","answer":"Bitget provides traditional APIs and faster execution suitable for high-frequency strategies. GMX requires blockchain interactions which add latency but offer complete transparency and no API rate limits."},{"question":"How do liquidation mechanisms differ between the platforms?","answer":"Bitget uses traditional order book liquidations with insurance funds. GMX employs oracle-based liquidations with immediate settlement, reducing systemic risk but potentially creating price impact during volatile periods."}]}]
